The declension of this noun was subject to a couple of minor variations:

* The inflected forms often featured an [[epenthetic]] /e/ before the /r/, especially in late Old English. For example, ''w√¶teres'' (gen. sg.) and ''w√¶tere'' (dat. sg.) might appear in place of expected ''w√¶tres'' and ''w√¶tre''. This reverses an earlier sound change from prehistoric Old English, where short /√¶/ and /e/ were regularly lost in word-internal open syllables when the preceding syllable was stressed.

* Similarly, the nominative/accusative plural varied between the expected form ''*w√¶ter'' and ''*w√¶t(e)ru''. The form with ''-u'' reverses another prehistoric sound change, where word-final /i/ and /u/ were lost following a [[w:syllable weight|heavy syllable]] or two light syllables. This makes ''w√¶ter'' part of a small class of neuter nouns which vary between the (expected) unchanged plural and an innovative plural ending in ''-u''. Other examples are ''w«£pn'' ~ ''w«£pnu'' (‚Äúweapons‚Äù), ''tƒÅcn'' ~ ''tƒÅcnu'' (‚Äúsigns‚Äù), ''bƒìacn'' ~ ''bƒìacnu'' (‚Äúsignals‚Äù), ''setl'' ~ ''setlu'' (‚Äúseats‚Äù), ''leƒ°er'' ~ ''leƒ°ru'' (‚Äúcouches‚Äù), ''wƒÅgrift'' ~ ''wƒÅgriftu'' (‚Äúcurtains‚Äù), ''seƒ°l'' ~ ''seƒ°lu'' (‚Äúsails‚Äù), ''botl'' ~ ''botlu'' (‚Äúdwellings‚Äù), ''wolcn'' ~ ''wolcnu'' (‚Äúclouds‚Äù), ''weder'' ~ ''wedru'' (‚Äústorms‚Äù), ''br√¶ƒ°n'' ~ ''br√¶ƒ°nu'' (‚Äúbrains‚Äù), ''wundor'' ~ ''wundru'' (‚Äúmiracles‚Äù), ''tungol'' ~ ''tunglu'' (‚Äústars‚Äù), ''√æ»≥rel'' ~ ''√æ»≥rlu'' (‚Äùholes‚Äù), and ''swefn'' ~ ''swefnu'' (‚Äúdreams‚Äù).

