===Etymology===
Possibly related to Proto-Uralic {{m|urj-pro|*wete}}, the source of Finnish {{m|fi|vesi}} and Hungarian {{m|hu|v√≠z}}. The nature of the relationship is unclear and controversial; the word may have been borrowed from Proto-Indo-European into Proto-Uralic, or the reverse. A minority of linguists suggests a common origin from an even earlier proto-language, but this is not generally accepted.

In Proto-Indo-European, the active elemental {{m|ine-pro|*wed-||water}} was contrasted with the passive {{m|ine-pro|*h‚ÇÇep-||body of water}}, similar to the opposition of the active "fire" {{m|ine-pro|*h‚ÇÅnÃ•g ∑nis}} with the passive {{m|ine-pro|*p√©h‚ÇÇwrÃ•}}.

