While it does have third conjugation forms, this verb is irregular. In Romance, it was regularized into a second conjugation verb ''*vole≈ç'' (present infinitive ''*volƒìre''), apparently based on the present participle ''volƒìns'' (that is probably inherited, like {{m|la|iƒìns}} from {{noncog|itc-pro|*jents}}, and also the model for the formation of the perfect ''voluƒ´''), just like most forms of {{m|la|possum}} were regularized to fit a second conjugation stem *''potƒì-''. Its present infinitive, ''velle'', descends from the athematic infinitive form {{cog|itc-pro|*wel≈ç|*wel-zi}} (''*-zi'' being the source of the usual infinitive ending ''-re'' as well). The second person singular present form ''vƒ´s'' is suppletive and belongs to the root {{cog|ine-pro|*weyh‚ÇÅ-|t=to strive after, pursue}}; the original form appears to be preserved as the conjunction ''vel'' (from Proto-Italic ''*wel-s'').
